Here’s the exact coding example using the Cook & Customer analogy to explain JavaScript Callbacks.
Press enter or click to view image in full size

JavaScript CallbacksExample 1: Basic Callback
// Customer function (Callback)
function customer() {
console.log("🍽️ Customer is eating the food.");
}// Cook function
function cook(callback) {
console.log("👨‍🍳 Cook is preparing the food...");
console.log("✅ Food is ready.");
// Call the customer after cooking
callback();
}
// Pass customer as a callback
cook(customer);
Output
👨‍🍳 Cook is preparing the food...
✅ Food is ready.
🍽️ Customer is eating the food.Example 2: Callback with Delay (Simulating Real Cooking)
function customer() {
console.log("🍽️ Customer starts eating.");
}function cook(callback) {
console.log("👨‍🍳 Cook is preparing the food...");
// Cooking takes 3 seconds
setTimeout(() => {
console.log("✅ Food is ready.");
callback();
}, 3000);
}
cook(customer);
Output
👨‍🍳 Cook is preparing the food...(Wait 3 seconds)
✅ Food is ready.
🍽️ Customer starts eating.
Example 3: Passing Data to the Callback
function customer(food) {
console.log(`🍽️ Customer is eating ${food}.`);
}function cook(food, callback) {
console.log(`👨‍🍳 Cooking ${food}...`);
setTimeout(() => {
console.log(`✅ ${food} is ready.`);
callback(food);
}, 2000);
}
cook("Pizza", customer);
Output
👨‍🍳 Cooking Pizza...(After 2 seconds)
✅ Pizza is ready.
🍽️ Customer is eating Pizza.
Visual Flow
cook(customer)
│
▼
Cook starts cooking
│
▼
