▼
Customer eats the foodWhat Happens Internally?
function customer() {
console.log("Customer is eating.");
}function cook(callback) {
console.log("Cooking...");
callback(); // Executes customer()
}
cook(customer);
When you write:
cook(customer);JavaScript internally treats it like this:
callback = customer;Then, when callback() is executed:
customer();So, callback() and customer() refer to the same function because the customer function was passed as an argument. This is the core concept of a callback function in JavaScript.
